:formula_10

For &quot;n&quot; up to 30, the cyclotomic polynomials are:

:formula_11

The case of the 105th cyclotomic polynomial is interesting because 105 is the least positive integer that is the product of three distinct odd prime numbers (3×5×7) and this polynomial is the first one that has a coefficient other than 1, 0, or −1:

:formula_12

==Properties==

===Fundamental tools===

The cyclotomic polynomials are monic polynomials with integer coefficients that are irreducible over the field of the rational numbers. Except for &quot;n&quot; equal to 1 or 2, they are palindromes of even degree.

The degree of formula_13, or in other words the number of &quot;n&quot;th primitive roots of unity, is formula_14, where formula_15 is Euler&#x27;s totient function.

The fact that formula_13 is an irreducible polynomial of degree formula_14 in the ring formula_18 is a nontrivial result due to Gauss. Depending on the chosen definition, it is either the value of the degree or the irreducibility which is a nontrivial result. The case of prime &quot;n&quot; is easier to prove than the general case, thanks to Eisenstein&#x27;s criterion.

A fundamental relation involving cyclotomic polynomials is 

:formula_19

which means that each &quot;n&quot;-th root of unity is a primitive &quot;d&quot;-th root of unity for a unique &quot;d&quot; dividing &quot;n&quot;.

The Möbius inversion formula allows formula_20 to be expressed as an explicit rational fraction:

:formula_21

where formula_22 is the Möbius function.

This provides a recursive formula for the cyclotomic polynomial formula_23, which may be computed by dividing formula_1 by the cyclotomic polynomials formula_25 for the proper divisors &quot;d&quot; dividing &quot;n&quot;, starting from formula_26:

:formula_27

This gives an algorithm for computing any formula_20, provided integer factorization and division of polynomials are available. Many computer algebra systems, such as SageMath, Maple, Mathematica, and PARI/GP, have a built-in function to compute the cyclotomic polynomials.

