===Integers appearing as coefficients===

The problem of bounding the magnitude of the coefficients of the cyclotomic polynomials has been the object of a number of research papers.
If &quot;n&quot; has at most two distinct odd prime factors, then Migotti showed that the coefficients of formula_13 are all in the set {1, −1, 0}.

The first cyclotomic polynomial for a product of three different odd prime factors is formula_42 it has a coefficient −2 (see above). The converse is not true: formula_43 only has coefficients in {1, −1, 0}.

If &quot;n&quot; is a product of more different odd prime factors, the coefficients may increase to very high values. E.g., formula_44 has coefficients running from −22 to 23; also formula_45, the smallest &quot;n&quot; with 6 different odd primes, has coefficients of magnitude up to 532.

Let &quot;A&quot;(&quot;n&quot;) denote the maximum absolute value of the coefficients of formula_23. It is known that for any positive &quot;k&quot;, the number of &quot;n&quot; up to &quot;x&quot; with &quot;A&quot;(&quot;n&quot;) &gt; &quot;n&quot;&quot;k&quot; is at least &quot;c&quot;(&quot;k&quot;)⋅&quot;x&quot; for a positive &quot;c&quot;(&quot;k&quot;) depending on &quot;k&quot; and &quot;x&quot; sufficiently large. In the opposite direction, for any function ψ(&quot;n&quot;) tending to infinity with &quot;n&quot; we have &quot;A&quot;(&quot;n&quot;) bounded above by &quot;n&quot;ψ(&quot;n&quot;) for almost all &quot;n&quot;.

A combination of theorems of Bateman and Vaughan states that on the one hand, for every formula_47, we have
:formula_48
for all sufficiently large positive integers formula_49, and on the other hand, we have
:formula_50
for infinitely many positive integers formula_49. This implies in particular that univariate polynomials (concretely formula_1 for infinitely many positive integers formula_49) can have factors (like formula_13) whose coefficients are superpolynomially larger than the original coefficients. This is not too far from the general Landau-Mignotte bound.

